%I A395942 #20 May 21 2026 17:11:59
%S A395942 0,1,3,31,2172,306509,179418338,252455740274,992630399965445
%N A395942 Number of inequivalent tilings of an n X n grid by 1 X p rectangles using the prime partitions of n^2 into prime parts p <= n up to symmetry.
%C A395942 For each prime partition of n^2 into prime parts p <= n, tile an n X n grid using one 1 X p rectangle for each part p in the partition.
%C A395942 Rectangles may be placed horizontally or vertically.
%C A395942 Tilings equivalent under rotations or reflections of the square are counted only once.
%C A395942 A395943 counts the corresponding distinct symmetry variants.
%C A395942 For n = 2..9, the ratio A395943(n)/A395942(n) increases toward 8.
%H A395942 Sean A. Irvine, <a href="https://github.com/archmageirvine/joeis/blob/master/src/irvine/oeis/a395/A395942.java">Java program</a> (github)
%H A395942 Chuck Seggelin, <a href="https://github.com/CSeggelin/SqTile">SqTile</a>, GitHub. This repository contains source code used to compute the terms of A395941, A395942, and A395943, and a slide deck describing the technical challenges in the implementation.
%e A395942 a(4) = 31 because there are 9 inequivalent ways to tile a 4 X 4 grid with eight 1 X 2 rectangles, 17 inequivalent ways to tile it with five 1 X 2 rectangles and two 1 X 3 rectangles, and 5 inequivalent ways to tile it with two 1 X 2 rectangles and four 1 X 3 rectangles. Thus 9 + 17 + 5 = 31.
%Y A395942 Cf. A000607, A395941, A395943.
%K A395942 nonn,hard,more
%O A395942 1,3
